##In Italy, 4 Chinese keep diary of Epidemic Prevention

Wechat, boyangcongpeople

The function introduces, peels off the human shell, records the real sensible life. Presented by the in-depth Reporting Department of the Beijing News.

###

Editor | Xiaoshu Chen proofread | Lucie

This article is about 4,503 words long and takes about 9 minutes to read

This is the first time that the Chinese people living in Italy have experienced a siege.

Ten days ago, Italian Prime Minister Contes announced in a televised address that Italy would impose a nationwide ban on the city.

Life began to change. When people go out, they need to take with them a personal statement, stating the place and purpose of their trip, there will be a police check on the way; the supermarket salespersons wear masks, in order to control the flow of people, customers need to line up at the door, in batches; in the Bar, the bar seats have been completely closed, the waiter in the wine, the glass will be placed on the empty table next to the guests, to avoid close contact.

As of March 19, there were 33,190 new coronavirus cases in Italy, 3,405 deaths and 4,440 cures, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 41,035, according to the latest figures from the Italian Ministry of Health.

Hospitals are full and supplies short, but Italians at home remain optimistic and entertaining. Every afternoon in Rome, people from many blocks would go to their balconies to sing, play musical instruments and play music.

The outbreak has also disrupted the plans of many Chinese Italians. In the face of the epidemic, the Chinese were the first to be alert and take action. Many of them chose to stay in the area and "fight the epidemic" with the Italians.

Milan businessman Xu Jianping

"Stay and do something for the Chinese. "

Xu, who runs a clothing business, has been in Milan for 25 years. It used to be a busy time for tourism in Milan, with many fashion weeks and exhibitions. Xu often meets many Chinese celebrities in the city, but now sees few Chinese.

Xu Jianping's clothing store is also closed, and he spends his days at home with his family watching the news.

'No one could have predicted that the outbreak in Italy would develop so quickly, ' he said. In January, many Chinese in Italy were still fighting the epidemic in China. Xu Jianping, from Wenzhou, Zhejiang Province, is the president of the Overseas Chinese Entrepreneurs Association in Milan. On Lunar New Year's Eve, he and other overseas Chinese leaders decided to cancel the annual Spring Festival parade and save 100,000 euros to buy relief supplies and find a way to send them home.

When Xu started shopping in late January, a disposable medical mask cost just 5 cents and a dupont protective suit only 5 euros, but the price of all the protective materials has risen many times since then, it's getting harder and harder to buy. "We sent everything we could raise to Italy, and from then on it was very difficult to get masks, goggles and so on. "

Many local Chinese are tempted to return home.

Many of Xu's family and friends have also advised him to consider returning to China for a period of time, but he said that as the president of the local chamber of Commerce, he should not think about leaving at such a time and should try to do something for the Chinese.

On Feb. 27, Xu received 8,500 masks and more than 1,000 bottles of disinfectant from France. The supplies were originally scheduled to be shipped to Wenzhou, but the overseas Chinese Federation of Zhejiang Province, aware of the severity of the Italian epidemic and the lack of supplies, directly coordinated the transfer to Milan.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Xu Jianping and members of overseas Chinese delegation hand out masks to care for Chinese. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Afterwards, Xu Jianping received materials from Dubai, Spain and other countries one after another. After receiving the materials, he and other members of the overseas Chinese group began to release news in their circle of friends and various hometown groups, and distributed free masks and disinfectant at designated places, standard Protective clothing was sent to the local Infectious Disease Hospital in Milan. Some Chinese have also produced tens of thousands of copies of the anti-epidemic pamphlets, distributed at the entrance of Milan Cathedral.

Xu Jianping, in Milan confirmed that the majority of Chinese bar owners. After some Chinese were diagnosed, because the condition is mild, the doctor gave them medicine, asked them to go home quarantine. "This situation makes a lot of people feel dissatisfied. Some people may think that they are targeting the Chinese, but the doctors are treating them equally. With medical resources being tight, the mayors of two Italian cities have been diagnosed with mild illness and have not been admitted to hospitals. "

A few days ago, Xu saw that some hospitals in Milan had begun to set up temporary "shelter hospitals" in the square, like inflatable tents, to screen suspected cases. At the same time, the government plans to convert a large convention center into a temporary hospital, which, if all goes well, will be completed in six days, with a capacity of 600 beds.

"We still have confidence in Italy's medical care, " Xu said.

Chen Qian, a Roman student

Faced with a severe epidemic, Italians have become "balcony djs"

In Rome, 600 kilometers from Milan, Chen Qian, a Chinese student, remembers the day of the siege as "a lot of people went to the station to take the last night train and run south. "

On March 10, Chen Qian, a vocal music student, was attending a choir class at his school. In the middle of the class, the principal suddenly opened the door and let everyone in. That night, in Lakoue pulled back to Rome in the car, saw the Prime Minister Contes announced the closure of the city news.

On the first day of the siege, many bars, pizzerias and ice cream parlors were closed. 'Italians can't live without these three things, ' Chen says. It was hard to find a restaurant that was still open, but it was only allowed to take to go. They asked that only one customer be allowed in at a time. After the food was packed, the waiter took a chopstick and handed it over with a handle from a plastic bag.

Since then, Chen has drastically cut back on his outings. He goes to the supermarket every few days to stock up on grain and buy lots of meat, vegetables, eggs and milk at a time.

This is his fourth year in Italy. When the outbreak first hit, mom called, hoping he'd come home.

He also thought of and around the international students, like many flights home. But now, to fly from Italy, you have to provide a medical certificate from a hospital that says you don't have an infection. Roommate two days ago packed his bags ready to return to the country, carrying a suitcase to the airport, only to be told that there is no proof, had to carry a suitcase back.

Chen Qian decided to stay in Italy. "The epidemic in China is not over yet, and if I have the virus, it will only make things worse if I go back. I should be able to stay here and not go out. "

Now, in the supermarkets of Rome, some precautions have been taken. The supermarket limits the flow, when the line checkout, everybody automatically maintains one meter distance, also stands in front of the cash register separates the customer and the cashier the glass baffle.

An empty street below the home of Chen Qian. Photo provided by interviewee

The number of people wearing masks has also increased. When the local cases were first confirmed in Italy, many of us (Chinese students) were already lining up to go to the pharmacy to buy masks, Chen said. When the Italians see us buying masks, they think we've been diagnosed and they'll stay away. If a Chinese person coughs or sneezes on a bus or any other public transport, everyone will get off.

When the closures were announced, face masks were still available in Roman pharmacies, with a limit of five per person, but they are no longer available.

Some medical supplies are also running low. "although Italy has one of the highest medical standards in the world, it does not have enough manpower and material resources, doctors and medical equipment. " In these idle days at home, Chen Qian spends more time surfing the Internet and watching television, he's always worried about what's on the news.

Two days ago, he saw a news at home. It showed a very old woman squatting at the hospital gate crying. Her husband had died of new pneumonia, and she had been diagnosed with it, but the doctor said that her condition is not as serious as the others, can not enter the hospital, can only go home alone quarantine. "It's hard to watch, but it's hard to watch. "

While hospitals are full and supplies short, Italians at home remain optimistic and entertaining. Below the TV screen, the zoetrope scrolls with the latest news of the outbreak, but there is no shortage of entertainment on TV.

Every day at 6 pm and 9 pm, people in many neighborhoods go to their balconies to sing, play instruments and play music. In the neighborhoods where young people live, they even became "deck djs" -- as if bringing a DJ deck and Stereo onto a balcony and getting everyone High.

In the music school alumni crowd, Chen Qian always sees the announcement, and calls for people to take their instruments to the balcony and open the windows during these two periods, making Italy a big free concert. A few days ago, Chen's brother Shi posted a video in a friend's circle. In the video, the brother sang a song "my Sun" on the balcony, and people living nearby opened their windows and shouted "Bravo! Bravo! "

On an ordinary day, outside the window of Chen Qian's house, the normally busy streets became quiet. The street vendors were gone, and only a few joggers or dog walkers were on the road.

Many people stopped working, and the owner of the downstairs pizzeria, wearing a black mask that covered his mouth and his nose sticking out, sat in front of the shop waiting to make a pizza.

At 6 p.m. , Chen Qian opened the window and let the music play out. He sat in his room and played guitar. He didn't sing much. Across the street, there was an empty football field. No one would answer him.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The owner of the pizza shop downstairs was sitting in front of the shop, waiting to make pizza. Some stores open for take-out. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Wang Shixiong, a teacher of advanced studies at Siena

Chinese people help each other. Old Friends give them shelter

Further education teacher Wang Shixiong's plan has also been disrupted. He would have been studying in Siena for another year and a half, but his family back home worried about him every day, and even his grandfather, who had never learned to use wechat, began to check in with his friends on a daily basis.

Classes at Wang's school continued until early March. The campus is located in the most popular part of Siena, next to the railway station and shopping center. The three-story building has few classrooms and a tight schedule of classes, and every day the hallways are crowded with students waiting for classes.

Wang Shixiong tried to warn the professor of the dangers of group classes, but the professor told him, "eat more oranges, by improving physical quality to fight the virus. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wang Shixiong in Siena Post Office to see the anti-epidemic guide. Photo courtesy of the respondents

In desperation, Wang Shixiong spent 12 euros to buy protective goggles and face masks integrated protective equipment to wear, carry disinfection water out of doors. Walking on the road, he can feel someone pointing at him behind his back, in order not to hear these do not want to hear the words, he put on headphones.

Wang Shixiong said that at that time many Italians thought it was just ordinary flu. His teacher also said in class, "I'm an old man and I've had a lot of colds in my life. Colds have been a regular occurrence since kindergarten. We don't have to worry about this virus, it's just a cold. "

On the evening of March 4, when Italy announced a national class suspension, Wang Shixiong watched students go to bars and nightclubs in the city center to "celebrate" the sudden holiday, while he stayed alone in his room, which smelled of disinfectant, watching myself stock up on a sack of potatoes and a bag of onions makes me feel like I'm in two different parallel universes with the crowd outside.

After the siege, on March 13, Wang Shixiong decided to leave Siena, where local hospitals had filled up with patients from other areas. He moved to Rome, where the epidemic was not yet severe, and stayed in a bachelor flat provided by his Italian friend, Gustavo.

Eight years ago, he and Laogu met in Beijing, Laogu sick, he had accompanied him to the Beijing Hospital. Wang Shixiong thought, fortunately there are friends to help, and this house as his "shelter. ".

Before he left, a Russian friend came to see him off. Wang Shixiong gave him some disinfectant and protective equipment. He remembers going to class wearing a mask and goggles in the early days of the outbreak and being treated as a "patient" by many of his classmates when the Russian friend came and sat down next to him and said, "I'm not afraid of you. ".

Stella, a student in Milan

After the city was sealed off, the Italians became wary

Stella, a Chinese student who has lived and studied in Milan for four years, has not left her home in almost a month.

Her memories of SARS make her more alert than most locals. When six new cases of pneumonia were detected in the towns around Milan at the end of February, she took precautions. Chinese students are expected not to attend classes even if the school continues, she said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Two old men were walking their dogs downstairs at Stella's House. Although they wore masks, they covered only their mouths and their noses were exposed. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Milan announced a curfew on February 24th: entertainment venues, including bars, were set to be closed for the night and the Grand Venice Carnival was shut down.

The entertainment-oriented nation immediately showed its dissatisfaction and lack of understanding of the move. "Why should the carnival be stopped when the Italians think we are in good health? There are people carrying signs and banners marching in the streets. "

Three days later, under pressure from industry and residents, the curfew was lifted. The mayor of Milan, Giuseppe Sarah, even took to Instagram to say that Milan is too warm a city to let it go. Milan is a safe place, a desolate street scene that makes one feel sad.

There are no masks on the Italian's daily list. In their eyes, only people with severe infectious diseases need to wear masks. "Not many people would wear them because it would mean admitting that they are sick. "

The first to act were Chinese students studying abroad. "On February 21, Chinese supermarkets were very busy, and the next day a Chinese supermarket was closed because it was out of stock or had too much to deliver. "

The day before the city was shut down, Stella bought a lot of stuff online from the supermarket. "I felt like I had to stock up, " she said, relying on four large bags of fruit and vegetables, vitamins, Napkins and dried beans to last her until the end of the month, "yesterday I saw that I was booked for delivery on the 30th. " Stella opened the APP Today to double-check, but she found, "No more appointments. "

Stella keeps a lot of beans at home, she says because she won't be able to exercise for a while, wants to stay in shape, and is less hungry when eating whole grains. Photo courtesy of the respondents

After the siege, the Italians began to be vigilant, the square was empty. It was only in the last few days that people began to walk down the street. Sometimes Stella would open the window facing the street in her room, and someone would be running, someone would be walking the dog. "people realized that life had to go on. " People continued to take the streetcar to work, and there were people next to each other on the subway.

But at night, the city became strangely quiet. Italians love to play, and if there was no epidemic, the bars and the canal zone at night would be a place for young people to gather. At the BISTRO, they pay ten euros for a drink and sit for hours. "That's all gone now. "

Stella, who is graduating this year, had planned to send in her résumé and apply for a job, but everything stalled because of the epidemic. It was never going to be easy for the Chinese to stay and work in Italy, and now it's getting harder.

On the Internet, some Chinese students are begging for a way back to China, saying they are "scared, panicky and unable to sleep" . But Stella didn't have time to think. She had several final papers waiting for her, and her project for the next semester was already online.
